Let me reconsider the problem. Maybe the issue isn't with the extractelement validation, but with the reduction logic itself. The SLP vectorizer is creating an incorrect reduction tree for select instructions.

Looking at the original code pattern:
- %s1 = select %1, %c1, false  
- %s2 = select %s1, %c3, false
- %s3 = select %s2, %c3, false

This is essentially: if (%1 && %c1 && %c3 && %c3) then true else false

But the vectorized version is doing something completely different.

Perhaps the SLP vectorizer should not be trying to vectorize this kind of select chain at all, especially when the conditions involve potentially poisonous values.

But I think I need to look at a different approach. Let me check if there's a specific condition in the reduction logic that should prevent this transformation.

Actually, let me look at the `getInsertExtractIndex` function again. Earlier I thought the operand index was wrong, but maybe that's where the real fix should be.

Looking at the template function:

```cpp
template <typename T>
static std::optional<unsigned> getInsertExtractIndex(const Value *Inst,
                                                     unsigned Offset) {
  static_assert(std::is_same_v<T, InsertElementInst> ||
                    std::is_same_v<T, ExtractElementInst>,
                "unsupported T");
  int Index = Offset;
  if (const auto *IE = dyn_cast<T>(Inst)) {
    const auto *VT = dyn_cast<FixedVectorType>(IE->getType());
    if (!VT)
      return std::nullopt;
    const auto *CI = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(IE->getOperand(2));
    if (!CI)
      return std::nullopt;
    if (CI->getValue().uge(VT->getNumElements()))
      return std::nullopt;
    Index *= VT->getNumElements();
    Index += CI->getZExtValue();
    return Index;
  }
  return std::nullopt;
}
```

The issue is that `IE->getType()` for ExtractElementInst returns the scalar type (i32), not the vector type! So `dyn_cast<FixedVectorType>(IE->getType())` will always fail for ExtractElementInst.

That's the real bug! For ExtractElementInst, I need to get the type of operand 0 (the vector), not the instruction's type.

Let me fix this function instead.

```bash
grep -A 15 -B 5 "template <typename T>.*getInsertExtractIndex" /llvm-autofix-deps/llvm/llvm/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp
```

